  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'Does valerian root actually help with sleep?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'A meta-analysis of 16 randomized controlled trials published in the American Journal of Medicine found that valerian "might improve sleep quality without producing side effects." Results are more modest than prescription sleep medications but meaningful for mild-to-moderate insomnia. Valerian works best after 2-4 weeks of consistent nightly use — it is not a single-dose sleep aid like melatonin. The mechanism involves increasing GABA availability in the brain by inhibiting GABA breakdown and enhancing GABA receptor binding. Studies show reduced sleep onset latency (time to fall asleep) and improved subjective sleep quality with 300-600mg of standardized extract taken 30-120 minutes before bed.' } },
  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'How does valerian root work?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Valerian root contains valerenic acid and isovaleric acid — compounds that inhibit the enzyme GABA-transaminase, which breaks down GABA in the brain. By inhibiting this enzyme, valerian increases GABA availability at synapses, enhancing the brain\'s natural calming neurotransmitter system. Valerian also contains compounds that bind directly to GABA-A receptors, similar to (but much milder than) the mechanism of benzodiazepines. Additionally, valerian may interact with adenosine receptors and serotonin receptors, both of which are involved in sleep regulation. The multi-target mechanism is why valerian produces a gradual, gentle sedation rather than a sudden knockout effect.' } },
