    <h2 id="why-valerian">How Valerian Root Promotes Natural Sleep</h2>

    <p>Valerian root (Valeriana officinalis) is one of the oldest herbal sleep remedies in human history. Hippocrates described its medicinal properties in the 4th century BCE. Galen prescribed it for insomnia in the 2nd century CE. Today, it remains the most widely used herbal sleep supplement in Europe and is included in the European Pharmacopoeia as a recognized sedative herb. Unlike melatonin (which regulates circadian timing) or prescription sedatives (which force sedation through strong GABA receptor agonism), valerian provides gentle, natural sleep support by optimizing the brain's own GABA system.</p>

    <div class="key-stat">
      <span class="key-stat-num">2,000+</span>
      <p class="key-stat-txt">years of documented use as a sleep remedy. A modern meta-analysis of 16 RCTs found valerian <strong>"might improve sleep quality without producing side effects."</strong> Valerian is most effective after 2-4 weeks of nightly use, as its GABA-optimizing effects compound over time — unlike single-dose medications.</p>
    </div>

    <p>Valerian's primary active compounds — valerenic acid and isovaleric acid — work by inhibiting the enzyme GABA-transaminase, which breaks down GABA in the brain. By slowing GABA destruction, valerian effectively increases GABA availability at synapses, enhancing the brain's natural calming system without introducing external sedatives. Additional compounds in valerian bind directly to GABA-A receptors and interact with adenosine and serotonin receptors. This multi-target, gentle mechanism is why valerian produces relaxation without the "drugged" feeling of prescription sleep aids.</p>

    <div class="info-cards">
