    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Valerian Root Gummies</h2>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Does valerian root actually help with sleep?</summary><p>A meta-analysis of 16 RCTs found valerian "might improve sleep quality without producing side effects." Best after 2-4 weeks of nightly use. 300-600mg extract, 30-120 minutes before bed. Works by increasing GABA availability in the brain.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>How does valerian root work?</summary><p>Valerenic acid inhibits GABA-transaminase (GABA breakdown enzyme), increasing GABA availability. Also binds GABA-A receptors directly and interacts with adenosine/serotonin receptors. Multi-target mechanism produces gentle, natural sedation.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Is valerian root better than melatonin?</summary><p>Different purposes. Melatonin regulates sleep timing (circadian). Valerian calms the mind (GABA enhancement). Racing thoughts: try valerian. Misaligned sleep schedule: try melatonin. Both can be combined. Valerian has no known dependency risk.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>How long does valerian root take to work?</summary><p>Acute: mild sedation within 30-60 minutes. Optimal: after 2-4 weeks of nightly use. Studies lasting 4+ weeks showed stronger effects. Unlike melatonin (first-dose effect), valerian requires patience and consistency.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Can I take valerian root every night?</summary><p>Yes, safe for nightly use for 4-6 weeks based on clinical trials. No dependency or withdrawal reported. Some herbalists recommend cycling (4-6 weeks on, 1-2 weeks off). Long-term data beyond 6 months is limited.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Does valerian root have side effects?</summary><p>Minimal at recommended doses. Occasional headache, dizziness, GI discomfort, vivid dreams. Strong earthy smell (gummies mask this). Do not combine with sedatives, alcohol, or sleep medications. Stop 2 weeks before surgery.</p></details>

